  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation combating money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades. Here's a comprehensive overview:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international recognition of money laundering as a criminal offense\n- Initial focus on reporting large cash transactions\n\n2. International Developments\n- FATF (Financial Action Task Force) established in 1989\n- Developed global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Created 40 recommendations for comprehensive AML frameworks\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones\n- US Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- Patriot Act (2001) - enhanced reporting and monitoring requirements\n- EU Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Enhanced Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Stricter customer due diligence requirements\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Regulations covering digital currencies\n- Cryptocurrency transaction monitoring\n- Enhanced digital reporting mechanisms\n- Machine learning and AI-based detection systems\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Broader corporate accountability\n- More comprehensive beneficial ownership disclosure\n- Enhanced penalties for non-compliance\n\nThese developments reflect growing complexity in financial crimes and technological innovations.",
